# gen40 (capstone): critical decoding -- the KB's beliefs constrain the learned
# generator. When the running output is a claim "<x> is a ___", any continuation
# the KB knows false is vetoed, so the language model cannot utter something the
# system rejects. This is the point of the whole decode arc: an LLM-like
# generative surface disciplined by inference. Held-out tokens.
> learn sequence: tweety is a plane
< Learned 3 transition(s).
> learn sequence: tweety is a plane
< Learned 3 transition(s).
> learn sequence: tweety is a bird
< Learned 3 transition(s).
# Frequency alone would say "plane" (seen twice) -- see gen_freq. But:
> tweety is not a plane
< Learned: not plane(tweety).
# Generation refuses the known-false claim and takes the next-best continuation.
> say tweety
< tweety is a bird
# Block every candidate and it stops at "a" rather than asserting a falsehood.
> tweety is not a bird
< Learned: not bird(tweety).
> say tweety
< tweety is a
# A non-claim sequence is unaffected -- the filter only guards "<x> is a ___".
> learn sequence: red apple pie
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> say red
< red apple pie